@article{WOS:000296063200023,
  abstract = {Experiments were made to evaluate the impact of the floral activity of
the insect visiting fauna on Abelmoschus esculentus (L.) Moench
(Malvaceae) seed yields. Two lots of 753 flowers (in 2009) and 634
flowers (in 2010) were differentiated according to the presence or the
absence of protection for insect visits. The foraging entomofauna, the
rhythm of insect activity, the fruit set rate and the mean number of
seeds per pod were recorded. Results showed 9 and 4 insect species in
2009 and 2010 foraged on A. esculentus flowers. Among them, two wild
bees Eucara macrognatha and Tetralonia fraterna were predominant with
92.2\% and 97.5\% of the total insect visits. Apis mellifera was poorly
represented in 2009 by 3.3\%. Insects foraged throughout the day light
period. Their activity was highest in the morning hours (9: 00
a.m.-10:00 a.m.). Bee species showed a specific behaviour close to
pollen harvesting and then promoted okra pollination. The mean number of
matured seeds, per pod from unprotected flowers (82.3 \& 93.3), was
significantly higher than that of flowers protected from insect activity
(76.2 \& 82.4) in 2009 and 2010, respectively. The percentage of the
mean number of matured seeds assigned to anthophilous insects was 7.4\%
in 2009 and 11.6\% in 2010. The installation of the nest of E.
Macrognatha and T. fraterna close to A. esculentus field is recommended
to improve the seed production of okra. (C) 2011 Friends Science
Publishers},
