@inproceedings{WOS:000234185300004,
  abstract = {Phylogenetic hypotheses for the largely South African genus Pelargonium
L'Her. (Geraniaceae) based on DNA sequence data from nuclear, plastid,
and mitochondrial encoded regions were synthesised into a single
hypothesis for 149 species. Pelargonium, a characteristic element of the
Cape Floristic Region, was found to consist of five main clades,
structured in two (subgeneric) clades that correlate with chromosome
size. Contrasting evolutionary strategies and speciation modes among
these clades can be inferred based on patterns of biogeographic
distributions and dispersal capacity, pollination biology and
karyological diversification. After the tree was made ultrametric its
nodes were dated based on an age estimate of 41 million years (mya) for
the Geraniaceae clade. This yielded 30 mya for the genus itself, 22 mya
for the winter-rainfall clade (comprising almost 60\% of the total
number of species known in the genus), 18 mya for the xerophytic clade
nested within it and harbouring geophytes, stem and leaf succulents.
Nested within the xerophytic clade is a clade comprising ca. 80 species
from the geophytic Pelargonium section Hoarea, all characterised by the
possession of (a series of) tunicate tubers, and dated at 10 mya. The
xerophytic clade is considered the result of an older (species-level)
radiation, possibly in response to late-Miocene aridification events.
Stem succulence (resulting from cambial activity), leaf succulence, and
tuber formation are hypothesised as putative key innovations that may
have triggered this radiation. Several shifts in pollinators, and
generally a trend towards longer-tongued insects, are inferred
predominantly from the xerophytic clade phylogeny. In the section
Ligularia/Hoarea lineage, sister clade comparison yields a highly
significant correlation between increase in clade size and shift to
long-tongued fly pollinators, and, in section Hoarea, the presence of
`tunicate tubers'. The geophytic radiation, nested in the xerophytic
one, is interpreted as a non-adaptive radiation vegetatively, but,
because of its high pollinator dependence, as an adaptive radiation
florally. Other, smaller, winter-rainfall clades exist within
Pelargonium. The fact that they did not proliferate as much as did the
main winter-rainfall clade may be attributed to absence of cambial stem
succulence and tuber formation.},
