@inproceedings{WOS:000082419500024,
  abstract = {Sixty-two characters that represent both new evidence generated by
recent studies and evidence derived from an earlier monograph of the sub
family Phytelephantoideae (Palmae) serve as basis for a number of
cladistic analyses conducted on both a matrix that combine all evidence
and subsets thereof. vegetative morphology and leaf anatomy (25
characters), staminate morphology and palynology (23 characters), and
pistillate and fruiting morphology (14 characters). The
Phytelephantoideae represent a long branch in the palm phylogeny, which
poses several problems when outgroup comparisons are made. Homologies of
some of the classification bearing characters of the ingroup are hard to
establish at the outgroup level, and the analysis will instead rest on
variation patterns in character complexes such as habit, leaf
morphology, leaf anatomy, and palynology that are known to be
homoplastic in palms at the tribal and subfamily level. The same
characters may, however, provide valuable information at the ingroup
level, where fewer character transformation events separate the tare. To
circumvent these problems, Ammandra is used as functional outgroup in
all the analyses. The evolution of five pollination ecological
characters is mapped on one fully resolved tree that is among the most
parsimonious solutions in both the analysis of the vegetative data, the
staminate flower data? and the combined data. The hypothetical
reconstructions show a sequence of events in the evolution of
phytelephantoid palms that reflects relationships with the pollinating
insects, mainly beetles. We conclude that additional studies of
phytelephantoid palms over the past 6 years has contributed to a better
understanding of the evolution within the group and has provided
stronger support for the existing taxonomy.},
