@article{WOS:000325304300004,
  abstract = {Thirty individuals of Euterpe edulis Mart. (Arecaceae) were observed in
an agroforestry system on Santa Catarina Island to determine phenology,
floral morphology, reproductive system, nectar production, visits by
social bees (Apidae: Apini) and fructification during two flowering
periods from November 2008 to March 2010. Flowering period lasted from
September to March, with means of 4.2 inflorescences per palm, starting
with the male phase and ending with the female phase. Male flowers
produced nectar in the morning and female during the whole day. Visiting
bees were Apis mellifera, Plebeia droryana, P remota, P emerina and
other Meliponina in flowers of both sexes and two species of Bombus in
male flowers. Fruit maturation occurred from July to September. Palms
formed 2.3 infructescences per palm with a mean of 2100 fruits. Insect
pollination was necessary for fruit formation. The species produced more
fruits after cross-pollination but self-pollination was also accepted.
Stingless bees of the genus Plebeia were considered potential
pollinators. The possibility to handle their populations might increase
fruit formation through the increase in pollinator abundance.},
