@inproceedings{WOS:000085946900025,
  abstract = {Starch gel electrophoresis was employed to investigate isozyme variation
in 128 accessions of 26 Elymus species originating in Europe, Asia and
North and South America. The enzyme systems used were aconitase (ACO),
diaphorase (DIA), glucose phosphate isomerase (GPI), malate
dehydrogenase (MDH), phosphoglucomutase (PGM) and shikimate
dehydrogenase (SKD), The electrophoretically detected banding patterns
were analysed and compared for each species considered. Fixed
heterozygosity was displayed for GPI in all species examined, thus
confirming the alloploid nature of Elymus. In general, considerable
isozyme variation was observed among accessions both within and between
species. However, intra-accession variation was infrequent, indicating a
predominantly self-pollinating reproduction system in these species, In
addition, different banding patterns were species-specific. The patterns
observed also reflected the genome relationships between the taxa,
separating the tetraploid Elymus in two groups, i.e., species containing
the SY genomes and those with the SH genomes.},
