@article{WOS:000088738600006,
  abstract = {Thirty races of Mexican maize (Zen mays ssp. mays) and 13 accessions of
teosinte (Zea mays ssp. parviglumis, ssp. mexicana and ssp.
huehuetenangensis) were surveyed for the presence of
restorer-of-ferility (Rf) alleles for S-type cytoplasmic male sterility
(CMS-S). Seven of the 13 teosinte accessions carry CMS-S restoring
alleles. All but three races of maize carry S restorers; an additional
two related races exhibit a low frequency of Rf alleles. The five races
of maize with no or low frequency of Rf alleles are all highland races
from central Mexico. Other studies have shown that members of this
racial group did not contribute to the Southern Dent or Northern Flint
maize that constitute the varieties from which most of US inbred lines
are derived. Forty-eight of the Rf alleles isolated From 25 races of
maize were tested for their homozygous viability by self pollinating
heterozygous (Rf/rf) plants. Judging from the normal seed set and pollen
records, none of the newly identified Rf alleles exhibits zygotic
lethality. Thus, we have identified naturally occurring restorers in
these races since any Rf mutations arising in the course of these
studies are expected to be zygotic lethals. The widespread occurrence of
Rf alleles in normal cytoplasm Mexican maize and its: wild relatives.
the teosintes, supports the hy pothesis that these represent genes
involved in normal mitochondrial function, some alleles of which are
also capable of restoring S male-sterile cytoplasm to fertility.},
