@inproceedings{WOS:000235034300013,
  abstract = {Phenotypic characters can undergo convergence and thereby confound
efforts to infer phylogenetic relationships. Here I consider several
plant lineages with strongly supported molecular phylogenies, and ask
how identifying and excluding phenotypic characters undergoing
convergence would affect the inferred pattern of relationships. In core
Liliales, Calochortus and Liliaceae sensu stricto are often considered
sister to each other, based on their shared possession of bulbs,
visually showy flowers, capsular fruits, wind-dispersed seeds, and
narrow, parallel-veined leaves. Analysis of rbcL and ndhF sequence
variation shows that Liliaceae are instead sister to Clintonia-Medeola,
which possess rhizomes, inconspicuous flowers, fleshy animal-dispersed
fruits, and broad, reticulate-veined leaves. Calochortus is sister to
Tricyrtis, and both are sister to Prosartes, Streptopus, and Scoliopus;
these genera share several of the phenotypic traits seen in
Medeola-Clintonia. Core Liliales thus provide a striking case of
concerted convergence, in which several different, seemingly unrelated
traits have arisen independently in different lineages as adaptations to
a shared suite of ecological conditions. Invasion of open, seasonal
habitats was accompanied by the independent evolution of bulbs, showy
flowers, capsules, wind-dispersed seeds, and narrow, parallel-veined
leaves in Calochortus and Liliaceae s.str.; persistence in shady
habitats was accompanied by the retention of rhizomes, inconspicuous
flowers, animal-dispersed seeds, and broad, reticulate-veined leaves in
their sister groups. Cladistic analysis of all phenotypic characters
resolves a fleshy-fruited clade, but exclusion of traits that appear to
have undergone concerted convergence results in a phylogeny that is
nearly identical to that obtained using cpDNA data. Such felicitous
results may, however, prove to be more the exception than the rule. In
Commelinaceae, sexual selection has apparently driven repeated
parallelisms in androecial structure, apparently to attract pollinators
to flowers that lack nectar but possess various forms of showy anthers
and antherodes that promise a pollen reward; exclusion of androecial
characters from the phenotypic phylogenetic analysis leads to a massive
loss of resolution.
In Rapateaceae, analysis of all phenotypic data produces a phylogeny in
which tribe Schoenocephalieae is early-divergent rather than terminal
(due to its independent evolution of nectaries and other traits
associated with hummingbird pollination), in which subfamily
Rapateoideae is resolved as monophyletic (due perhaps to developmental
linkages among gynoecial traits), and in which relationships among major
lineages within Rapateoideae are unresolved. Excluding phenotypic traits
that seem unlikely to be independent trackers of phylogeny results in
loss of most phylogenetic structure. A similar result arises in the
Hawaiian lobeliad genus Clermontia, whereby several species appear to
share a homeotic mutation in which the outermost whorl (sepals) have
assumed the size, shape, color, texture, and deciduousness of the inner
whorl of petals. Given the far greater number of molecular vs.
morphological characters obtained in most current studies of plant
lineages, the tendency for molecular characters to display a higher
degree of phylogenetic consistency, the ready ability to test whether
independent molecular datasets contain congruent phylogenetic signals,
and our present inability to predict, a priori, which phenotypic
characters are likely to undergo convergence in which lineages, it seems
likely that the most productive approach to the analysis of phenotypic
evolution will remain the overlay of phenotypic features on phylogenies
derived from molecular data or, where both phenotypic and molecular data
are consistent, the combined datasets. The studies presented indicate
that any comprehensive attempt to develop a deep understanding of
morphological evolution must incorporate genetic, developmental,
ecological, and phylogenetic dimensions. Comparative biology is not
enough, nor is ``Evo-Devo{''}; we must adopt an ``Eco-Evo-Devo{''}
approach.},
