@inproceedings{WOS:000086521700040,
  abstract = {Of the 668 plants that were studied, five died and 22 became badly
damaged during the 10 year experimental period. From the 93\% of the
labelred plants that coned, the gender ratio appears to be 1.2. The
percentage of the plants that coned in different years varied from
virtually zero to 71\%, without a clear governing factor being evident.
Greater water availability appears to intensify coning without altering
the coning pattern from year to year. The male plants coned mon
frequently than the female plants. On average the males coned once every
3.5 years whilst the females coned once every 5.5 years. Pollination
appears to be exclusively by wind. Although beetles (Metacucujus
transvenosi) are abundant in the pollen shedding male cones, they do not
appear to visit the female cones. The optimal temperature for the
germination of the cycad seed appears to be about 20 degrees C. The
average rate of stem elongation of the cycad at the Modjadji Nature
Reserve for the period 1991 to 1996 was found to be 52 mm per year.},
