@article{WOS:A1979HW06600010,
  abstract = {This contribution on V. angustifolium Ait., sweet lowbush blueberry
(Ericaceae), is the first of a series presenting biological information
on plants that are components of the flora of Canada. V. angustifolium
is a deciduous low shrub endemic to North America, whose range in Canada
extends from the east coast of Newfoundland to Lake Winnipeg in
Manitoba. It occurs from Quebec 57.degree. N {[}north latitude] to
Virginia 38.degree. N. To produce fruit the flowers usually require
cross pollination by wild bees or related insects. The fruit of V.
angustifolium is edible and matures during late summer. During the past
30 yr in the Atlantic Provinces of Canada many field abandoned from
other forms of agriculture are brought into stands of this species by
burn-pruning and selective weed control.},
