@article{WOS:A1979HW62100002,
  abstract = {The characteristics of pollen cementing (stickiness; total amount,
structure and distribution of the pollenkitt; fine structure of the
exine) were studied in Salix caprea, Populus nigra, P. tremula
(Salicaceae), Tilia platyphyllos, T. tomentosa (Tiliaceae) Erica
herbacea, Calluna vulgaris and Andromeda japonica (Ericaceae). The
homogeneous, electron-dense pollenkitt of S. caprea fills up the
interbacular caves completely and is also situated on the outside layer
of the exine, so the pollen is sticky and insect-pollination dominates.
In contrast the homogeneous, mostly electron-dense pollenkitt of P.
nigra and P. tremula, remains largely in the loculus while only a small
amount moves to the exine caves; the tectum is free of pollenkitt, so
the pollen is powdery and the result is wind pollination. In T.
tomentosa and T. platyphyllos the mostly electron-dense (in part, also
foamy) pollenkitt is located largely in the caves, but also in small
amounts on the outer layer of the exine; the pollen is only of medium
stickiness and pollination both by insects and wind is possible. In E.
herbacea, C. vulgaris and A. japonica, there is no pollenkitt sensu
stricto: in the loculus, tapetum-borne irregular globuli do not adhere
on the exine; their nature remains obscure; there are no viscin-threads.
Because of the Streukegel-mechanism, the powdery pollen of the described
Ericaceae allows wind pollination.},
