@article{WOS:A1979JA25900005,
  abstract = {A collection of 151 cultivars of cauliflower was tested for
self-incompatibility and horticultural value under Polish climatic
conditions. The mode of inheritance of self-incompatibility in
cauliflower and a number of different S-alleles were determined. The
value of homozygous self-incompatible lines for F1 hybrid production was
also investigated. Cultivars belonging to the group of summer
cauliflowers, mainly cultivated in the temperate climate, are
self-compatible. Most of the self-incompatible plants occurred in the
group of cultivars from the tropical climate, mainly Indian cultivars.
The highest percentage (62\%) of self-incompatible plants was found in
the Indian `'Pusa Katki''. Inheritance of self-incompatibility was
analyzed in `'Pusa Katki'' and also in 2 other Indian cultivars, PI
277277 and PI 271445. The self-incompatibility system in cauliflower is
the same as in other botanical varieties and species of the Cruciferae,
it is sporophytic and determined by 1 series of multiple S-alleles.
S-alleles in heterozygous genotypes showed 4 types of interaction in
pollen grains and in the pistil. Activity of recessive S-alleles in
heterozygous genotypes was lower and changed within the range of 0-72\%
as compared with dominant and codominant S-alleles, the activity not
less than 90\% changed within the range of 10\% only. The activity of
the same S-allele in different heterozygous combinations changed
depending on the 2nd S-allele interacting with it. In the homozygous
self-incompatible lines of `'Pusa Katki'', `'PI 277277'' and `'PI
271445'' 7 different S-alleles were identified. These lines were used
for the production of 3-line F1 hybrids. The maternal forms of these
hybrids were F1 obtained by crossing 2 homozygous self-incompatible
lines with different S-alleles. The lines in a pair were similar to each
other in such characteristics as height of plant, shape and color of
leaves, earliness of curd creation and curd quality. The father
components (pollinators) were self-compatible selfed lines (I2) obtained
from 3 early summer cultivars. Three-line F1 hybrids differed
considerably in the commercial crop of curds and their quality. These
differences were dependent on reciprocal crosses of maternal F1. This
suggested the influence of cytoplasm on the inheritance of curd quality.
Some of the 3-line hybrids were characterized by an early, uniform crop
of high-quality curds. The breeding of F2 hybrids in summer cauliflower
is possible, as is the case with other botanical varieties and species
of the Cruciferae.},
