@article{WOS:000237410600003,
  abstract = {The endangered fragrant prickly-apple cactus (Harrisia fragrans Small)
is known exclusively from early successional, disturbed scrub habitat in
southeast Florida. Scrub habitat is characterized by infrequent high
intensity fire that Occurs about every 20-75 years as scrub succeeds
from an open, shrub-dominated community to one dominated by a closed
canopy of sand pine. Plants in this community have evolved methods (seed
germination, resprouting, etc) to perpetuate their populations following
fires. The result of two prescribed fires in the area where this rare
Cactus Occurs indicates that the cactus is killed by fire. No seed
germination or resprouts were observed from three known fragrant
prickly-apple cactus that were burned during two fires. In addition,
during two nights of observation, a common species of beetle (Anelaphus
inermis) was observed inside the flower of this plant, but it was
unclear if this beetle is the sole pollinator. Based on these limited
observations, we question if this cactus is an endemic or an introduced
species that has survived in highly disturbed landscape. Further
research is needed on the effects of fire on the reproduction of this
species.},
