@inproceedings{WOS:000082419500013,
  abstract = {The present study compares the floral scent composition at the generic,
specific, and subspecific level in the palm tribe Geonomeae to
investigate at which of these levels variation is found and whether such
variation follows systematic groupings. Floral scent was collected using
headspace adsorption and analysed by coupled gas chromatography-mass
spectrometry. The study included 28 taxa belonging to five of the six
genera of Geonomeae: Pholidostachys? tone species), Calyptrogyne (two
species), Asterogyne tone species), Welfia tone species), and Geonoma
(23 taxa in about 15 species). The floral scent composition showed
variation among genera and species and within species complexes. Most
chemical compound groups in the scent were distributed irrespective of
taxonomic levels, and most taxa, even within species complexes, could be
separated on the basis of floral scent composition alone. It is
concluded that variation in floral scent chemistry probably is selected
for by ethological isolation among co-occurring taxa and that floral
scent chemistry is important in maintaining reproductive barriers
between taxa of geonomoid palms. Furthermore, variation in floral scent
chemistry is important in speciation processes within species complexes.},
