@article{WOS:000249402700008,
  abstract = {Astragalus alopecurus Pallas (syn. Astragalus centralpinus
Braun-Blanquet) is a glacial relict listed in the Red Data Book and
grows on only one site in Bulgaria, a stony, grassy more or less open
habitat on marbleized limestone in the coniferous belt at Beglika,
Western Rhodopes Mts. Data on floral ecology gathered in 2003 and 2005
included pollen viability and germination, stigma level in relation to
anthers, flower size, inflorescences/stalk, stalks/plant, flowers
opening daily on an inflorescence and the number of days open. Flowers
in insect exclosures did not set fruit. Pollinators included Bombus
hortorum (the most active) and B. agrorum workers, while B. pratorum and
some others were recorded rarely. Bumblebee species composition varied
within years and through space (big patches versus small patches of A.
alopecurus). Pollinators collected nectar, transferred the pollen
sternotribically and demonstrated high flower constancy. Natural seed
set showed at most only two of the 7-10 ovules/flower matured to seeds.},
