@article{WOS:A1982NB01000001,
  abstract = {G. leucopteris is a conspicuous shrub in the Irwin Botanical District of
southwestern Australia. Flowering peaks during early summer, while
anthesis is nocturnal and synchronized with peak odor and nectar output.
The nectar contains moderate levels of sugars and amino acids. From
studies of plants growing 180 km south of its normal range, this species
is hemiphilic and polyphilic. Few of the many insects attracted to the
flowers are effective pollinators. The most important are the nocturnal
scarab beetles and (from laboratory studies), to a lesser extent, small
marsupials. Flower opening is usually triggered by effective pollinators
with almost immediate removal of pollen. The stigma is not receptive
until the next night. The species is self-compatible, with selfing
(autogamy and geitonogamy) probably accounting for most seed set.
Protandry usually fails as an outbreeding device (xenogamy) because of
staggered anthesis within and between conflorescences. Pollinators
essentially move pollen geitonogamously from flowers in a staminate
condition to those in a pistillate condition. The low level of
fertilization (14\% of mature flowers) indicates that the
conflorescences are functionally andromonoecious. The low seed set (6\%
of mature flowers) is primarily due to the limited, carrying capacity of
the rachis. This is offset by a long flowering season, rapid follicle
maturation and high seed viability. Seeds are wind dispersed and, from
observations of cultivated plants, may be buried by ants or eaten by
granivorous birds. Glandular hairs over much of the plant are
resiniferous and may protect if from herbivores, as they do not appear
to enhance pollination, increase drought resistance or capture enough
insects to serve as an indirect nutrient supplement. G. leucopteris has
many traits favoring it as a woody pioneer (nomad), including selfing in
the absence of pollinators (spontaneous autogamy).},
