@inproceedings{WOS:000082419500009,
  abstract = {The recently presented circumscription of species: complexes (Henderson.
1995) is evaluated for three species of Bactris (B. hirta Mart. var.
pectinata {[}Mart.] Henderson. B. simplicifrons Mart. from Venezuela,
and B. maraja Mart. var. maraja from Venezuela and Peru) and two
varieties of Geonoma macrostachys Mart. from Peru and Ecuador. For these
species. data are available from pollination studies of their
populations. A reconsideration of the systematic status of species and
their varieties is attempted not by means of morphological. but by
reproductive characters, applying a biological species concept. Three
data records of species pairs or their respective varieties are
presented to look for the relative value of alternative characters in
the evaluation of morphological variability at the local and regional
scale. It is concluded that reproductive: characters, when linked up to
syndromes, may serve as indicators of identity or distinction of
species. The application of this method is, however, mush more rigorous
and profound at the local than at the regional scale. Reproductive
characters considered most important in these syndromes include
phenology, sexual activity, pollination strategy, spectrum of visitors,
and artificial pollination tests. Henderson's circumscription turns out
to be of high systematic relevancy, and taxa are confirmed also when
reproductive criteria are applied. The taxon Geonoma macrostachys Mart.
var. acaulis (Mart.) Skov is suggested to be retained as G. acaulis
Mart.},
