@incollection{WOS:000281460700002,
  abstract = {Breeding is the core of the evolutionary process of plants, of which the
basic life procedures include growing, surviving and breeding. The
selection of reproductive evolution in plants is powered by their
adaptation to the habitat. The choices of habitat in plants have
developed into various behaviours of clonal reproduction and sexual
reproduction, but it is the sexual reproduction and its crossing
advantages and selfing depression that usually attract attention, while
the fact that the plant serves its existence and multiplication better
via the reproductive assurance of clonal reproduction and selfing is
neglected.
Paphiopedilum armeniacum is an endangered orchid species, endemic to
China. During the period of April 2000 to October 2007, tests of
biological and ecological characteristics of P. armeniacum and its ex
situ reproductive modes had been carried out in Nushan Mountain, Yunnan
Province, to study the relationships between the climate, vegetation and
other environmental factors in original habitat and the growing,
surviving and breeding of P. armeniacum. P. armeniacum grows and
survives well in limestone areas. It has very strong abilities of
asexual and sexual reproduction, and it is endowed with the specialties
of highly effectively using its environment and tolerating bad
conditions, and with strategies of extending plant lifespan and escaping
death, as well as the ability to control the ageing process. P.
armeniacum is able to invade a forest environment with moderate
demolishment and those in the early period of restoration but cannot
live in large dense forests.
The population performances of P. armeniacum under different floristic
composition patterns were compared to determine how abundance of this
specie correlates with the floristic composition pattern. Based on the
floristic composition, four end groups of plots within this vegetation
at level 3 of the TWINSPAN program can be classified. The DCA ordination
of plots data showed that the variation in the floristic composition of
four groups appeared to be related to the disturbance degree, the
succession stage and the ground covering. There were probably two kinds
of succession series of population performances: one was under the site
where it was covered with shallow soil and rocky chipping and the
performance of population showed a trend from colonization stage to
expansion stage; the other was under the site where it was covered with
deeper soil and the population development exhibited a slight downtrend.
The difference of population performance based on different succession
series further indicated that the P. armeniacum was a semi-shaded
species with low competitive abilities in well-developed soil, and the
reproduction of this species was restricted by the growing condition
that was considered to be of optimization.
P. armeniacum has two modes of asexual reproduction-by tillering and by
producing rhizomes. Tillering of asexual reproduction is of strong
vitality and is endowed with an emergency mechanism to cope with
harmfulness by producing numerous rhizomes. The purpose of clonal
reproduction is to extend the lifespan of genets, to implement the
sexual reproduction and to increase the proportion of sexual mating. The
rhizome reproduction in P. armeniacum is also an adaptation to the
condition of defoliation or to the condition covered with soil in order
to escape from death. P. armeniacum still keeps the original
reproductive pattern in ex situ habitat with an obviously different
condition from the original one. Clonal genets also keep the patterns of
growing, surviving and breeding, which are adaptive to the uncertain
conditions after returning to the original habitat. All further indicate
that its reproductive mode has evolved from ecological adaptation to
genetic adaptation.
P. armeniacum is able to produce many seeds through sexual reproduction
and the seeds can grow into new genets effectively. It deceives various
pollinators among populations to achieve selfing, crossing, or even
mixed mating in flowers by mimicking flowers of associated plants. In
conditions of unsaturated pollinators or external pollen,
self-pollination completed by pollinators could increase the seeds
production. The high inbreeding depression in the self-pollinating
estimate of this study showed that, as the pollinating environment
turned into an essential factor of reproductive assurance for wild
species, the increase of the selfing rate could increase the effect of
reproductive assurance. We demonstrated how the visiting behavior of
pollinating insects in a changeable pollinating environment influenced
the reproductive assurance. This demonstration indicates that flowers
with a strict cross-pollinating structure also have a selfing mechanism
and a changeable pollinating environment is propitious to the selfing
and the mixed mating, which associates the reproductive assurance with
the selfing rate of flowers of non-autonomous self-pollination via the
mechanism of mixed mating to display the diversity of mixed mating
evolution. The mix-breeding mode of P. armeniacum undounbtedly reflects
the success in evolution of flowering plants in terms of the diversity
of breeding strategies, and it also gives an answer to the question that
why the vast majority of plants have self-compatibility, or most plants
employ reproductive strategies of selling or mixed mating, although
crossing is of superiority.},
  address = {400 OSER AVE, STE 1600, HAUPPAUGE, NY 11788-3635 USA},
  affiliation = {Liu, ZJ (Corresponding Author), Orchid Conservat \& Res Ctr Shenzhen, Natl Orchid Conservat Ctr China, Shenzhen 518114, Peoples R China.
Liu, Zhongjian; Chen, Lijun, Orchid Conservat \& Res Ctr Shenzhen, Natl Orchid Conservat Ctr China, Shenzhen 518114, Peoples R China.
Liu, Zhongjian; Zhou, Qing, S China Agr Univ, Coll Forestry, Guangzhou 510642, Guangdong, Peoples R China.
