@article{WOS:A1968A775600002,
  abstract = {Six-plants of a self-incompatible population of L. crassa were grown
from seed collected in nature and cross-pollinated in all combinations.
The incompatibility relationships between sibs were determined in 11 of
the F1 families. A one-locus sporophytic incompatibility system was
established. None of the parents was homozygous at the S locus. At least
5, and possibly all 6, of the parents did not share an S allele. Only
one pair of alleles was shown to have different interactions in the
pollen and stigmata. The identity and expression of the S alleles were
determined in 6 families. Eight pairs of alleles were independently
expressed in both the pollen grains and the stigmata. Sixteen pairs of
alleles showed dominance of one allele over the other in the pollen
grains or the stigmata or both. F1 plants of 2 crosses between different
self-incompatible races were self-incompatible. F1 plants of 6 crosses
between self-incompatible and self-compatible races were
self-incompatible; in 5 of the families, the frequency of
