@incollection{WOS:000296536500001,
  abstract = {Freesia Klatt (Iridaceae: Crocoideae) is characterized by its regularly
netted corm tunics, sharply deflexed or horizontal flower spike, deeply
divided style branches, verrucose or papillate capsules, and subglobose
seeds with a glossy, smooth or lightly wrinkled testa lacking secondary
ornamentation. The genus comprises 16 species distributed through
sub-Saharan Africa, with a marked centre of diversity in the winter
rainfall region of the southwestern Cape. Molecular and morphological
evidence suggest a new classification in which the tubular-flowered
species previously segregated as subgen. Anomatheca (Ker Gawl.)
J.C.Manning \& Goldblatt do not comprise a monophyletic lineage but
represent three independent origins for the gullet-flowered species.
These data support the recognition of two subgenera, based on the
texture of the floral bracts: subgen. Freesia (8 spp.) is defined by its
soft-textured, green or translucent floral bracts, often with dark brown
tips; and subgen. Viridibractea (Goldblatt) J.C.Manning \& Goldblatt (8
spp.) is recognized by firm-textured, green bracts with narrow
translucent margins. Floral chemistry provides additional novel data
supporting this topology: p-ionone and dihydro-beta-ionone are
characteristic of all fragrant species in subgen. Viridibractea but are
absent from subgen. Freesia.
In subgen, Freesia, plants of F. grandiflora from Macuba, in
north-central Mozambique, with unusually short filaments and a
consistently pink perianth are recognised as subsp. occulta J.C.Manning
\& Goldblatt. Within subgen. Viridibractea, Freesia uiridis (Aiton)
Goldblatt \& J.C.Manning is segregated as the monotypic sect. Alatae,
defined by several autapomorphies, notably a winged stem, greenish or
brown flowers, and a 1-banded pollen operculum. The remaining species in
the subgenus comprise sect. Viridibractea, defined by two derived
characters: a papillate stem and oblique seeds with swollen raphe.
Species boundaries in sect. Viridibractea are particularly problematic,
and the recent discovery of several new, locally endemic species has
necessitated a re-examination of the taxonomy of the group. The
development of axillaiy cormels in F. alba and F. leichtlinii is a
previously overlooked feature that is diagnostic for the two species,
and populations until now recognized at species level as F. alba, are
distinguishable from F. leichtlinii only on the basis of their white
rather than pale yellow or cream-coloured flowers. They are accordingly
reduced to subspecific rank as subsp. alba (G.L.Mey.) J.C.Manning \&
Goldblatt. Subspecific rank is also re-introduced in F. uiridis for
inland populations with falcate, mostly crispulate leaves and shortly
lanceolate tepals, which are distinguished as subsp. crispifolia
(Goldblatt) J.C.Manning \& Goldblatt from coastal populations with
narrowly lanceolate leaves and attenuate tepals. The new species F.
praecox J.C.Manning \& Goldblatt is recognized for early-flowering
populations with narrow leaves from the southern Riviersonderend
Mountains that were previously included in F. alba but which differ from
it in ecology and in lacking axillary cormels. This revision covers
morphology, anatomy, molecular relationships, floral biology, taxonomy,
horticultural history and cultivation. Each species is described and
fully illustrated in colour and black-and-white, with complete synonomy,
notes on ecology, and distribution maps. A complete analysis of the
floral scent chemistry of 13 taxa is presented.},
