@incollection{WOS:000406818000013,
  abstract = {which, depending on the species, offer plenty of pollen and nectar, and
some other elements of bee pasture resin, and a secondary product,
honeydew. With a decrease in the intensity of the flowering of fruit
crop, the primacy in bee nutrition is slowly taken over by acacia and
lime pastures.
A large number of tests and experiments, carried out on the territory of
Serbia, especially in orchards mechanically isolated from other
pollinators, established that the introduction of honeybee and solitary
bee colonies greatly enhances the yield and quality of fruits per
hectare of plantation. The most pronounced impact of bees is on fruit
crops from the rose family (Rosaceae). Fruit pastures consisting
primarily of the species within the genera Prunus and Malus, offer
plenty of nectar and pollen. The attractiveness of pear flowers (Pyrus
domestica), due to the presence of caprylic acid in the nectar, was
considerably smaller, so in order to increase crop yields, honeybees
must be specially trained. Because of the long flowering season (May
September) and/or the abundance of pollen and nectar, blackberries
(Rubus fruticosus), strawberries (Fragaria vesca), raspberries (Rubus
idaeus) and chestnut (Castanea sativa) become a backup food source for
bees which is more extensively exploited during pasture rest periods
whereas on large plantations, or areas under crops, they are used as the
main pasture.
The most widespread pollinators of cultivated flowering plants are
honeybees, belonging to the genus Apis. Some 75-90\% of fruit orchards
in Serbia are pollinated by Apis mellifera. Fruit crop pollination is
assisted by strong{''} colonies, with adult bees in 8 out of 10 beehive
frames and 5 brood frames, i.e. some 20.000 to 32.000 adult bees. Hives
intended for pollination are transported to the site at the beginning of
the flowering season (when 15-20\% flowers open) when the danger of a
change in orientation onto a different nearby culture can be avoided. If
transported later, the effects of pollination will be reduced. Hives are
preferably arranged in zigzag lines, in groups of 10-15, and on flight
paths. In an apple orchard, the hives should be 180-270 m away from each
other and left there when 10-15\% flowers have blossomed. In order to
facilitate pollination of other fruit species, an adequate number of
hives per hectare are necessary to be provided and the following is
suggested: almonds 5-8, apples (depending on the cultivation method)
2-7, apricots 3, blueberries 7-10, nectarines 2-3, peaches 2-3, pears
2-3, plums 2-3, raspberries 3-4, strawberries 3-8, watermelons 2-7.
It is known that many flowering plants are efficiently pollinated only
by certain insect species so, in order to find and use the most
efficient pollinators, domestication of insects is resorted to.
Encouraged by successful domestication, orchard bee species used today
are: Osmia lignaria, 0. rufa and 0. cornuta. Around 500-600 0.
cornifrons females or about 600-1800 0. lignaria ones are enough to
pollinate 1 ha of apple orchard. To pollinate the same area, 2-6
honeybee hives, with thousands of bees, are required. The advantage of
Osmia bees over honeybees as pollinators is that they fly and visit
flowers at much lower temperatures (9-11 degrees C) which is what
honeybees do not do (they do not fly out at temperatures below 13
degrees C). They fly and pollinate in inclement weather in early spring
when temperatures are hostile for the activities of honeybees. 0.
cornuta are easily grown and reproduced, they do not share common
diseases or parasites with honeybees. Their maintenance does not require
great investments. Using such bees to pollinate orchards results in
high-quality crops, increased fruit production by 30\%, that is almost
unachievable by any other agrotechnical measures, and also in reduced
costs of orchard maintenance. However, in new plantations, with hail
nets, best results are achieved by combining solitary bees and
honeybees.
Bumblebees (Bombus spp.) have proven to be excellent for indoor
pollination, and at low temperatures, which is why they can be exploited
on plantations with high intensity management and anti-hail protection
systems.
Planned bee pollination can significantly mitigate, or even neutralize,
the loss of fertile flowers due to winterkill, the damage caused by
sudden drying of branches and twigs, or the appearance of the so-called
defective flowers, or premature rejection of flower buds and incomplete
flowering, as well as the losses brought on by cold and strong winds.
Planned pollination shortens the flowering season, which lowers the risk
of infestation through the flower, and also reduces the use of
pesticides. A planned organization and removal of colonies of
pollinating insects may have effect on yield and can help avoid crop
thinning, which significantly reduces production costs. Planned
pollination, therefore, provides more reliable fruit growing, better
quality products and also increases production efficiency.},
