@inproceedings{WOS:A1996BH44Y00025,
  abstract = {As part of a comprehensive investigation of the evolution and taxonomy
of Ernodea, populations of five taxa were studied on Great Abaco and
Great Inagua (Bahamas), and Puerto Rico. Observations on floral biology
revealed deviations from typical heterostyly; the species fall in a
category called `'Anomalous Heteromorphic group'' by Barrett. Styles and
stigmas are usually exserted and longer than the stamens, but
occasionally stigma lobes and anthers are at the same height without
reciprocal herkogamy. Pollen is dimorphic, even within single anthers,
with viability associated with larger pollen grains. The flowers were
visited by a suite of potential pollinators, primarily hummingbirds,
bananaquits and honey bees. Hand pollination experiments suggest that
there are no reproductive barriers between the species, and that each
species has a mixed-mating system (self-compatibility, outcrossing,
autogamy and the possibility of apomixis).},
