@article{WOS:A1977EV52700007,
  abstract = {Embryology of duku and langsat varieties of L. domesticum, an important
fruit tree species of southeast Asia, is fairly uniform, despite
differences in their habit and fruit structure. In duku the time taken
from floral initiation to open flowers is 7 wk, and ripe fruits are
formed 15 wk after flowering. Only 11\% of the flowers normally set
fruit, but on bagging the inflorescences at the floral primordia stage
21\% flowers set fruit. No pollen is formed in anthers of both varieties
due to degeneration of the sporocytes, but endothecium develops normally
even though the anther does not dehisce. The ovules are like those in
other Meliaceae, but there is a multiple archesporium forming multiple
embryo sacs, some after meiosis following the Polygonum type of
development, but others aposporously. Their growth is non-synchronous,
and only 1 embryo sac attains maturity. There is neither pollination nor
fertilizer, and the free nuclear endosperm develops autonomously. The
egg degenerates and adventive embryony results in 1-3 mature embryos in
a seed. About 60\% seeds degenerate during early development of the
embryo but the edible fleshy aril continues growth independent of the
fate of the seed within. Nearly 30\% of all viable seeds in duku and
52\% in langsat are polyembryonate.},
