@article{WOS:A1985ALN4900005,
  abstract = {Reciprocal hybridization was attempted between sibling pairs of plants
from 2 native populations of M. bigelovii and M. douglasii that differed
by 7\% in nuclear DNA content. Seven F1 hybrids were obtained. The
female parent of 5 was M. bigelovii and of 2 was M. douglasii. The
nuclear DNA amounts of the F1 progeny were not intermediate between the
parental values, but in all cases were within or exceeded the range of
the respective male parent. Three of 4 F2 families obtained from single
spontaneously self-pollinated F1 plants had DNA values that had reverted
back to or near the mean of their original female parental controls. A
4th F2 family segregated widely, but the majority of its members were
within the range of its original female parental controls. These data
provide further evidence supporting the previously proposed hypothesis
that biochemical mechanisms exist that adjust or destabilize the genomic
DNA amount in hybrids of Microseris whose parents differ in nuclear DNA
content. Changes are apparently possible both upward and downward from
the expected intermediate F1 value. DNA amounts do not necessarily
stabilize in the F1 as was apparent in a different cross between M.
douglasii and M. bigelovii. Instability and/or adjustment of nuclear DNA
content occurs at least to the F2.},
