@article{WOS:000303278500044,
  abstract = {Due to the different species of Epimedium separated by seasonal
isolation and geography, developing a method for mid-term storage of E.
pubescens is necessary to facilitate germplasm conservation,
interspecific hybridization and identification of hybrid species. In
order to optimize the process of hand-pollination, in this work we have
studied the conservation potential of E. pubescens pollen stored for
approximately 2 months at -20 degrees C, -70 degrees C and -196 degrees
C. The optimal desiccation time of E. pubescens pollen was found to be
210 min. In vitro pollen germination of fresh pollen was 56.0\%, and it
was progressively reduced after conservation at -20 degrees C, -70
degrees C and -196 degrees C reaching a minimum of 4.2\%, 6.0\% and
4.4\%, respectively after 2 months of storage. The germination capacity
of pollen stored at -20 degrees C and -196 degrees C was similar to that
observed at -70 degrees C, therefore for reasons of convenience and
economy, pollen can be efficiently stored at -20 degrees C. There were
no fruit set differences between the field pollinations performed with
stored pollen and pollinations performed with fresh pollen. These
results indicate that E. pubescens pollen can effectively stored at
subzero temperatures for several weeks to months.},
