@article{WOS:A1987M311400010,
  abstract = {Male flowers of andromonecious species can serve two functions: they can
increase the amount or quality of conspecific pollen reaching the
plant''s hermaphrodite flowers by providing greater pollinator
attraction than the hermaphrodite flowers alone could achieve (the
attraction hypothesis), and/or they can provide pollen that is carried
by pollinators to other plants (the donor hypothesis). I tested the
attraction hypothesis in the andromonoecious perennial Solanum
carolinense L.  (Solanaceae). In this self-incompatible species male
flowers are structurally and visually similar to hermaphrodite flowers,
but have reduced pistils. A series of experimental-garden and glasshouse
experiments suggested that male organs were required to make an
individual flower attractive to pollinators, but that the presence of
male flowers did not benefit hermaphrodite flowers on the same plant. In
one open-pollinated experiment, 77\% of hermaphrodite flowers with
intact anthers set fruit, but only 5\% of those with anthers removed did
so. (Hand pollination increased fruit set of de-anthered flowers to
50\%, so the surgical process itself was not a major cause of reduced
fruit set.) This experiment indicated that male organs (and hence both
male and hermaphrodite flowers) attract pollinators. In a second
pollinated experiment, fruit set of hermaphrodite flowers on plants with
male flowers present did not differ significantly from fruit set of
plants with male flowers removed (males present: 88\% fruit set,
.hivin.X = 0.310 g/fruit; males absent: 82\% fruit set, .hivin.X = 0.288
g/fruit). These results argue against the attraction hypothesis as an
explanation for the evolution of male flowers in this species.},
