@inproceedings{WOS:000235034300012,
  abstract = {Biomechanical properties and causal functional anatomy including
ontogenetic variation, are combined with plant systematics for a better
understanding of the evolution of plant growth forms. This
interdisciplinary and experimental approach is demonstrated in the genus
Aristolochia s.l. (Aristolochiaceae) and the subfamily Secamonoideae
(Apocynaceae s.l.) by analysing changes in stem biomechanics between
self-supporting and non self-supporting species. In a third example,
variation in hollow stem structure and its consequences for growth form,
ecology and evolution are discussed in relation to fossil and extant
Sphenopsids. In a fourth case study, we discuss initial results in a
reproductive system on the biomechanical significance of the staminal
lever system in the genus Salvia (Lamiaceae) and its potential
importance for the control of pollination and speciation.},
