@article{WOS:000283003200005,
  abstract = {On the causes of the differential seed production in the anficarpic
species Trifolium polymorphum (Leguminosae). Trifolium polymorphum is
recognized as one of the best adapted legume in field conditions. It
combines different reproductive strategies such as stoloniferous
vegetative reproduction and seed reproduction by two types of fruits
produced in underground and aerial flowers. These last ones are
chasmogamous and underground flowers are cleistogamous. A higher seed
production has empirically been detected in underground flowers rather
than in aerial ones. In the present work, embryological studies in
aerial and underground flowers were carried out in order to determine
the existence of ontogenetic causes which may promote productivity
differences in both types of seeds. No embryological pre-zygotic cause
