@article{WOS:A1991LE77800007,
  abstract = {The family Podocarpaceae represents a group of conifers with a
`'Gondwana'' distribution; centers of endemism include New Caledonia,
New Zealand, and Tasmania. Unlike most conifers, which have light, dry
wind-dispersed seeds, Podocarpaceae usually develop fleshy attractive
structures around each animal- dispersed seed. Like most gymnosperms,
many taxa secrete a drop of fluid from the micropyle of the ovule at the
time of pollination (pollination drop). However, the drop extends so
that it can pick up previously fallen pollen, a process referred to here
as `'pollen scavenging'': Pollen does not need to fall immediately and
directly on an existing drop. The larger and longer lasting `'target''
for pollen reception increases pollination efficiency and links
pollination mechanism and seed dispersal mechanism. Conifers'
reproductive diversity helps explain their evolutionary success.},
