@article{WOS:A1978FZ32700002,
  abstract = {There are 2 widespread Lumnitzera species in the mangrove community of
the Asian tropics: L. racemosa and L. littorea. In 1826
Gaudichaud-Beaupre proposed Laguncularia rosea from Manila, Philippines,
subsequently considered to be L. rosea or a mere color form of L.
racemosa. Its diagnosis and plate however clearly contrast with the
other species and indicate that it might be a hybrid between them. The
form L. .times. rosea is proposed. A pocket resembling in some
characters, but not all, the original description of L. rosea was found
at Missionary Bay on Hinchinbrook Island in northern Queensland,
Australia. This may represent another rare hybridization between the 2
spp. with, perhaps, some introgression toward L. littorea. Hybridization
would be rare because of the ecological isolation and because L.
littorea is primarily bird pollinated and L. racemosa is insect
pollinated.},
