@article{WOS:A1987L332000008,
  abstract = {The functional anatomy and morphology of Ficus asperifolia are
described. The differences between gall figs and seed figs are
established. Unlike the seed figs, gall figs lack a synstigma. The gall
flowers are equivalent to the seed flowers in the characters of the
embryo sac, but have specialized ovules that facilitate oviposition. In
early C phase, both gall and seed flowers show the entrance of a pollen
tube into the embryo sac, initial stages of plant embryo development,
and endosperm  formation. Would it not be for the developing wasps, the
gall flowers probably would produce seeds. Pollen transport and
pollination by wasps results in providing their offspring with plant
endosperm as a nutritive tissue. In the pollinating wasp of the
gynodioecious F. asperifolia, pollen pockets can be understood as finely
adjusted tools for the pollination in oviposited gall flowers and the
prevention of seed formation in neighbouring, not oviposited, gall
flowers, which would strongly  compete for space with the developing
galls.},
