@article{WOS:A1981MH48500024,
  abstract = {Compositae (Asteraceae) and Orchidaceae (with 20,000-25,000 spp.) are
the largest families of the angiosperms and show many advanced
characters. Although they are very variable in certain characters the
diagram of the flowers is rather uniform and both families are easily to
delimit. The orchids are characterized by a pronounced mycotrophy. This
is connected with: very small seeds without endosperm, anemochory, great
number of ovules, pollination by transfer of pollinia, very specialized
floral ecology combined with great variability in certain characters of
the flower (notably labellum and column). There are rather few different
life-forms in this family and the vegetative characters tend to be
relatively uniform in one genus. In the Compositae many small flowers
are united in a capitulum of flower-like appearance (pseudanthium).
Variability of the flower has been transferred to the capitulum.
Although the hermaphrodite flowers have an elaborate pollen-presentation
mechanism there is only very limited specialization in floral ecology.
Vegetative characters are extremely variable and there is also much
variation in fruit morphology and biology. The worldwide distribution of
both families contrasts with the small share they have of the
vegetation. Species numbers of both families in different regions show
that the orchids are poor in species if it is too cold or too dry. Many
Compositae show weedy tendencies and several have become firmly
established in other continents. The orchids are to a much larger extent
threatened by extinction through alteration of the habitats than the
Compositae. In both families many hybrids between species are known.
Internal reproductive isolation between species is especially rare in
orchids, whereas isolation by different pollinators seems to be rather
frequent. The chromosome numbers in both families are shown. They are
more variable in the Compositae (with the low numbers mainly in the
annuals), in the Orchidaceae n = 18-21 are the most frequent numbers.
The different path of evolution in the 2 families is elucidated by the
comparison of 2 well-known genera: Ophrys and Crepis. Ophrys species are
differentiated mainly in the flowers (in connection with a very special
way of pollination), vegetative characters and the fruits are very
uniform. In Crepis the flowers show only quantitative differences while
there is much variability in the involucrum, the fruits and the
vegetative characters.},
