@article{WOS:A1979HM35600017,
  abstract = {A population from southeastern Scotland of H. sphondylium L. ssp.
sphondylium, H. mantegazzianum Sommier and Levier and presumed hybrids
between them was studied. The existence of F1 hybrids was demonstrated.
These are morphologically intermediate and virtually sterile.
Backcrossing, although a rare occurrence, may take place. Phenotypic
variation in chromatographically obtained spot patterns was considerable
in H. sphondylium and the hybrids but not so in H. mantegazzianum.
Isolation barriers between the parental species are spatial and
ecogeographical, now largely cancelled by man''s introduction of H.
mantegazzianum, selective pollination by insects, low seed set with
cross-pollination, vegetative imbalance in the hybrid, and segregational
(perhaps also physiological) sterility. There is little evidence of
introgression. The hybrids are heterozygous for 2 translocations
involving 3 chromosome pairs and for 2 paracentric inversions in 2
pairs. A heteromorphic bivalent was found both in H. sphondylium and in
the hybrids.},
