@article{WOS:A1996WA89800002,
  abstract = {The various reasons for the paucity of collections of succulent Bulbine
species from the north-western Cape Province of South Africa include
their small stature, inaccessible habitats and the low number of plants
occurring in any single population. The plants often exist as rare
endemics. Five new species are described: Bulbine fragilis G.
Williamson, B. truncata G. Williamson, B. quartzicola G. Williamson, B.
torsiva G. Williamson and B. vittatifolia G. Williamson. Two species are
related to B. diphylla Schltr, two are not closely related to any
Bulbine species but bear some resemblance to each other, and the fifth
is related to B. margarethae L.I. Hall and B. fallax Poelln. The
descriptions of the new species are appended with critical remarks,
including the systematic affinities of each species, soil type, habitat
and climatic factors. Although Bulbine flowers appear superficially
similar, they are actually quite distinct in producing various levels of
fragrance, reflection of tepals, filament dimorphism and diagnostically
distinctive seeds. The orientation of the flowers ranges from facing
skywards to nodding and is probably related to specialised pollination
strategies. The filaments can display dimorphism varying from horizontal
to completely recurved. Anthesis is variable, with flowers appearing in
almost all months of the year and with opening varying from before
sunrise to after midday The different leaf and flower morphologies seen
in these Bulbine species, coupled with their distinctive habitats, point
to a highly complex group of plants with specialised adaptive growth and
pollination mechanisms.},
