@inproceedings{WOS:000272449900004,
  abstract = {The perennial plant Silene latifolia has emerged as a model system for
investigating the evolutionary and ecological basis of biological
invasions. This paper synthesizes the studies that have used a variety
of approaches (field observational, experimental, molecular) that
together provide a picture of how species may shift from being benign in
their native range to problematic upon introduction to a novel habitat.
This European species was introduced to North America about 200 years
ago. Common garden experiments conducted on both continents reveal that
there has been a significant evolutionary shift in life history traits,
as the North American plants consistently express a more aggressive
phenotype. A large-scale survey of populations across the species' range
in Europe and North America found enemy attack by generalists (floral
herbivory) and specialists (fruit predation, fungal disease) to be much
higher in the native range. We believe that this release from enemy
attack has played a major role in Silene's evolution. North American
plants invest less into potential defensive mechanisms (trichomes and
fruit wall) and are more susceptible to being attacked by the specialist
enemies upon reintroduction to a common garden in Europe. Taken
together, these patterns suggest that natural selection has favoured a
reallocation of energy from defensive traits to those conferring an
advantage in overall growth and performance (e.g., flower and fruit
production). However, there is also evidence that the colonization
history has influenced the biology of the species in North America.
Significant genetic structure in Europe along with an apparent
non-random introduction of the more aggressive Central European
phenotype may indicate that a founder event of a pre-adapted genotype
occurred. In sum, our work demonstrates how ecological and evolutionary
forces act in concert to influence the outcome of species'
translocations.},
